An Exploration of Carson Wentz's NFL career¶

By Hamir Ranade and Ausin Hwa¶

Motivation¶

Carson Wentz has been a sort of polarizing figure in the NFL (National Football League) because of his hit or miss performances. Many argue that he was a great Quarterback in the 2017 season, and was on track to be voted the league MVP, or Most Valuable Player, before he unfortunately tore his ACL, and had to watch from the benches as his backup QB, Nick Foles, won the 2017/2018 Super Bowl. After Foles had won, there was a huge controversy about who the Eagles should keep as their starter. Ultimately, they decided on Wentz; but his performance had started to decline. In the two seasons following the Super Bowl, Wentz put up seemingly-average stats (which we will examine), but many argued that he was a below average quarterback in 2018 and 2019. Following, in 2020, Carson Wentz had his worst season, leading the league in sacks and interceptions, and causing his team, the Philadelphia Eagles to have a record of 4 wins, 11 losses, and 1 tie. As a result of his poor play, Wentz wanted a fresh start and requested to be traded. Carson Wentz was traded to the Indianapolis Colts and is their new starting quarterback. However, even with the new start, fans are questioning his ability to lead a team. In order to analyze his talent and performance as a quarterback, we are taking data from all the seasons Carson Wentz played (2016 - 2020) and trying to find out if his 2017 season was uncharacteristically good for a quarterback, and then see if his other seasons were below par for a quarterback. We collected this data from https://www.pro-football-reference.com/, where you can access the data by season, player, or team. Furthermore, the website conveniently allows you to download the data as a .csv file, which we use to read into a pandas dataframe.

In order to complete this analysis, we will follow the data sciencep pipeline, which includes the steps: Data collection, Data management, Exploratory data analysis, Hypothesis testing, and drawing conclusions. For more information on the data science pipelines, you can read this article.

Since this analysis relies heavily on the knowledge of football, you can find some background information about football here.

If you want to read more into the quarterback controversy after the Eagles' Super Bowl 52 victory, you can read it at the following article.

Data Collection/Curation¶

We downloaded the data from the https://www.pro-football-reference.com/ website. It was contained in multiple CSV files. We used pandas to read theses CSV files. The data was pretty well formed for what we needed to do, there were a few columns that we felt like were not necessary for our purposes but we kept them just in case.

Data Representation¶

We want to separate our data by years, because we want to view each year individually, so we do not merge the dataframes yet. We then view our 5 tables. We chose to use tables to represent the data since they're easier to read.

Explanation of the columns¶

Rk: The column Rk is the rank of the quarterback based on the number of completions that the quarterback has thrown.
Player: Player is the player's name. If there is a *, it means that they were selected for the Pro-Bowl (A celebration for the best performing players in that year) If there is a +, it means that that player was selected to First Team All Pro (an award that selects the best player at a position to curate a team with the best player at each position)
Tm: The column Tm is the team to which the given quarterback belongs.
Age: The age column denotes the age the quarterback was in a given year.
G: The G column shows the number of games that the quarterback played.
GS: The GS column explains the number of games where that quarterback has started, or in other words, was the main quarterback in that given games
QBrec: The column QBrec shows the record of the team for which they played. It follows the format of Wins-Losses-Ties.
Cmp: Cmp is the number of completed passes to a receiver.
Att: Att is the number of attempted passes, regardless of wether or not it was caught.
Cmp%: This is similar to the previous two datapoints and it just takes Cmp divided by Att.
Yds: Yds is the total number of yards achieved by the quarterback.
TD: TD is the number of touchdowns that the quarterback has accumulated in the season
TD%: TD% is the total number of touchdowns to total number of pass attempts.
Int: Int is the number of interceptions (thrown balls caught by the defensive team) that the quarterback has accrued over the season.
Int%: Int%, similar to TD%, is the number of interceptions over the number of pass attempts.
1D: 1D is the number of first downs gained by the quarterback.
Lng: Lng is the longest pass thrown by the quarterback in the season.
Y/A: Y/A represents the average yards per pass attempt by the quarterback.
AY/A: AY/A represents the adjusts the aforementioned number for touchdowns and interceptions. It helps to adjust for the lack of yards gained by a touchdown, meaning it adds an extra 20 yards for a TD, instead of 10. It uses this formula to calculate it: (pass yards + 20 (pass TD) - 45 (interceptions))/(pass attempts)
Y/C: Y/C shows how many yards a quarterback would gain per completed pass.
Y/G: Y/G shows how many yards on average a quarterback would gain per game.
Rate: Rate shows the passer rating, which is based off of the pass attempts, completions, yards, touchdowns, and interceptions that a QB has in a game. The rating ranges from 0 to 158.3.
QBR: QBR is another way to rate the quarterback, developed by ESPN. It differs from the passer rating since it encompasses more than just the passing stats, such as sacks taken, or fumbles lost.
Sk: Sk represents the total number of sacks that a QB takes in a season, which is when they are tackled behind the line of scrimmage before they can pass the ball.
Yds.1: Yds.1 is labeled as yards, but in actuality represents the number of yards lost by sacks.
NY/A: NY/A is the net yards per attempt, which takes into account the amount of yards lost per attempt. The formula is as follows: (pass yards - sack yards)/(passing attempts + sacks).
ANY/A: ANY/A is the adjusted net yards per given attempt, which is similar to the AY/A, but taking sacks into account. The formula is as follows: (pass yards + 20 (num of TDs) - 45 (interceptions) - sack yards)/(pass attempts + sacks).
Sk%: Sk% is the percentage that the quarterback has been sacked, which follows the formula of (number of sacks)/(passing attempts + number of sacks)
4QC: 4QC is the number of comebacks led by the quarterback.
GWD: GWD is the number of game winning drives, meaning that the last touchdown in the game helped the team win the game.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In the Exploratory Data Analysis part of the data science pipeline, we analyzed the data in the hopes of identifying patterns.

Furthertmore, in this step we try and represent different variables of the data in multiple ways to see where Carson Wentz falls with respect to the rest of the league's quarterbacks. We tried to use the measurements that from our perspective were the most telling about performance. In football TD and interception ratio is an easy rule of thumb to say whether a quarterback is good or not. We also used some more sophisticated measurements like ESPN's QBR and Passer rating, which are ratings that take in many factors, and tried to compare players.

In [12]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

for df in df_list:
    # Filter out the quarterbacks who have started fewer than 4 games
    df = df[df['GS'] >= 4]
    # Create a linear regression line based on the number of TDs and Ints
    sns.regplot(x = 'TD', y = 'Int', data = df)

    # In all of the rows, label the one who is Carson Wentz
    for _, rows in df.iterrows():
        if (rows['Player'] == 'Carson Wentz\WentCa00') or (rows['Player'] == 'Carson Wentz *\WentCa00'):
            plt.annotate('Wentz', xy = (rows['TD'], rows['Int']))
    plt.show()

These graphs were taken from the list of starting quarterbacks who have started in at least 4 games. We did not want to populate the data with backup or fill-in quarterbacks since they will usually have a much higher ratio due to less playing time. In the graphs themselves, we can see from this that Carson Wentz had a better TD to Int ratio than the league mean in 3 of the 5 seasons, namely the 2017, 2018, and 2019 seasons, because having a point below the regression indicates that the player had more touchdowns than interceptions compared with the rest of the league. However this does not paint the whole picture, as number of completions and attempts is a big factor that is not taken into account. However, we can still see that Carson Wentz in 2017 had a great year and a bad year in 2020 due to his touchdown and interception ratio.

Hypothesis / Hypothesis Testing¶

Now that we've viewed the data, we believe that there are certainly years where Carson Wentz excelled at playing quarterback.

In our hypothesis testing, our null hypothesis will be that Wentz is not an above average quarterback. As football fans who are invested in Carson Wentz's career, we hypothesize that Carson Wentz is an above average quarterback. We will test our hypothesis with a 75% confidence level, meaning we'll have an of .25. We chose that confidence due to the fact that Carson Wentz has only been in the league for 5 years and to allow for flexibility in the case of errors.

In order to prove this, we will explore numerous statistics and compare those to the rest of the league. Furthermore, since the quarterback's performance varies greatly year over year, we decided to analyze Wentz's performance on a year-by-year basis.

Standardization of Data¶

In [16]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

# Create a violin plot to better see the data
sns.violinplot(x=qb_all['year'], y=qb_all['Rate'])
Out[16]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fc5009b7190>

Here we wanted to create a violin plot to look at the distribution of the data. In order to standardize our data and to get accurate information from z scores, we need to ensure that the data for every given year is normally distributed. Without a normal distribution, the z scores would not be an accurate measurement. Here from the violin plot, each year clearly shows a unimodal and mostly symmetric distribution of the data, meaning that we can go ahead and use z scores and standardization in order to complete our hypothesis testing.

In [17]:
import numpy as np

for df in df_list:
    # Create a list that will later turn into a column in the dataframe
    standardization = []

    # Create a numpy array out of the Passer Ratings
    year_arr = np.array(df['Rate'])

    # Find the mean and the standard deviation and store them in variables
    avg = year_arr.mean()
    std = year_arr.std()

    # Calculate the z score/standardized score by taking (actual - average) / (standard  deviation)
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        diff = row['Rate'] - avg
        stdized = diff/std
        standardization.append(stdized)

    df['std_passer_rate'] = standardization

plt.close()
years = [2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020]

j = 0

for df in df_list:
    # Sometimes there are Wide Receivers who, during trick plays, throw the ball. Since they threw the ball, their statistics were counted in the data, so we just filter out any position that is not a quarterback. 
    df_copy = df.loc[(df['Pos'] == "QB") | (df['Pos'] == "qb")]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()

    # Create a scatter plot with the Yards per game as the x values and the standardized passer rating as the y value. 
    ax.scatter(df_copy['Y/G'], df_copy['std_passer_rate'])
    sns.regplot(x = 'Y/G', y = 'std_passer_rate', data = df_copy)

    i = 0
    for name in list(df_copy['Player']):
        # Make the name legible
        name = name.partition("\\")[0]

        # Label Carson Wentz
        if name == "Carson Wentz" or name == "Carson Wentz *":
            ax.annotate(name, (list(df_copy['Y/G'])[i], list(df_copy['std_passer_rate'])[i]))
        i = i + 1

    ax.set_title(years[j])
    j = j + 1

    plt.show()

From these graphs, we can get a better idea of Carson Wentz's performance compared to his rating. Moreover, in these graphs, a better standardized rating over the yards per game signifies better quarterback performance. In other words, even if a quarterback throws, on average, more yards per game, those yards might not be as meaningful, since they might not lead to a touchdown, but are instead disrupted by interceptions or pass break ups. We can see that in Wentz's best year, 2017, he ranks highly in both criteria: Y/G and standardized passer rating, meaning he was fostering meaningful yards during the game and helping to lead the team to victory. In 2020, his worst year, the graph helps to show that even though he would average around 220 yards a game, they did not help him be successful as a quarterback since the standardized passer rating was much lower than the rest of the league.

for df in df_list:
    td_int = []
    
    # Create a column for the Touchdown to Interception Ratio
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        # If a quarterback threw no interceptions, just take the number of touchdowns
        if(row['Int'] == 0):
            td_int.append(float(row['TD']))
        else:
            td_int.append(float(row['TD'])/row['Int'])

    df["TD/Int"] = td_int

# This for loop standardizes the TD/Interception ratio
for df in df_list:
    std_td_int = []

    # Create an array for better management of data and store the mean and standard deviation into variables

    std = ratio_arr.std()

    # Calculate the standardization of data
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        diff = row['TD/Int'] - avg
        stdized = diff/std
        std_td_int.append(stdized)

    # Store the information into the dataframe
    df['std_TD/Int'] = std_td_int
    display(df.head())

Conclusion¶

We had hypothesized that Carson Wentz was an above average quarterback, and we tried to disprove that he was an average or below average quarterback through most of his career, however we had mixed results. As expected Carson Wentz had one standout season in 2017 in which he ranks clearly above most of the league's quarterbacks, however his other seasons are not so obvious. From our plots that we created, we can see that Carson Wentz often came out more favorably in three of his seasons, but unfavorably in the other two seasons. His two worst seasons were his first and his most recent. Oftentimes rookies underperform in their first season, so that is not too surprising. But we can also see that in his last season he had the most sacks in the league. This is very detrimental to a quarterback, as it means that they do not have enough time to throw and are constantly under pressure. This indicates our methods are lacking in some areas because we have not taken into account performance of the team in our models.

Football is a team sport, so if we could somehow correct for every team member's performance in the same year we could make more accurate claims. That being said, when we tested Carson Wentz's standardized TD/Int ratio and passer rating we found conflicting results. Because of our significance level of .25 we rejected our null hypothesis in three out of the five seasons when looking at Wentz's standardized TD/Int ratio. This matches our earlier findings indicating that in three of his seasons, Wentz was an above average QB. However, when we tested his standardized passer rating, we found that we could only reject the null hypothesis for his 2017 season. From these findings, it is still difficult to say if Wentz is better than the average NFL QB, but going season by season, it is easy to say that in two of the five seasons Wentz played, he was a below average QB, in one season he was an above average QB, and in the other two he was about average. Again, these statistics do not take into account how his team played, but if we are just looking at individual performances, I think we can be fairly confident in the former statement.
